/** The client's Number2Letter table. Reconstructed, not lifted verbatim: N.js keeps it as a
 *  scene gameAttribute rather than a literal, so it never appears as a table in the source.
 *  Evidence for the layout: (a) Gaming[12] — the purchased-super-bit string — begins with "_",
 *  and the client appends Number2Letter[0] as the first bit; (b) the sailing UI labels captain f
 *  with Number2Letter[f+1] and captain 0 shows as "A"; (c) `Number2Letter[digit+1]` maps digit
 *  0 -> "a" in the nametag renderer. All three agree on [0]="_", [1..26]="a".."z".
 *  The uppercase tail is INFERRED from usage (EventShopOwned(48) must resolve to "V", and
 *  OptLacc[311] on a real save contains "V" exactly when the Purple Chest Slug is owned —
 *  which independently corroborates the offset). Treat indices > 26 as inferred, not confirmed.
 *  HARD LIMIT, verified: this table only covers ids 0..52. `Number2Letter` is a Stencyl GAME
 *  ATTRIBUTE, not a literal in N.js — greps for `h.Number2Letter=` / `Number2Letter=` all return
 *  nothing, and the CJK glyphs a real save carries in Gaming[12] ("肢","者","肖","答",...) appear
 *  ZERO times in the client. So ids >= 53 are not recoverable from N.js at all. Callers that index
 *  past the end get `undefined` and MUST treat that as unknown, not as "not owned" — see
 *  superBitType() in artifactchance.mjs. */
export const NUMBER_2_LETTER = ["_", ..."abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz", ..."ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ"];

